value.0: This proud Elkenbeast gazes around at its surroundings skittishly. Scorch marks rim a ragged hole in its gut and the smell of burnt flesh hangs thick about the noble animal.
The animal gazes at you without fear, holding high its antlered head. You can't determine why it might be waiting there though it doesn't appear to be worried by your ignorance.
<StartAction>[DC: 13]</Start> The animal gazes at you without fear, holding high its antlered head.
<StartAction>[Failure]</Start> The elkenbeast ignores your whispers, content to lick pebbles from the cracks between the stones.
<StartAction>[Success]</Start> As it nuzzles close, you notice that the flesh beneath its soft white coat seems strangely warm for one so dead. "Greetings, Child of Man," it whispers back.
The elkenbeast draws close again, nibbling affectionately at your clothes. "Live your life, Child of Man. Live it to the full."
It sniffs the stagnant breeze, as if catching the smell of some distant meadow. "I died for a noble cause." Its liquid eyes catch yours. "What cause did you die for, Child of Man?"
The elkenbeast rears up on its hind legs, a white shadow against the featureless mists. "I died that hope might live."
"Worry not," whispers the Elkenbeast. "In every grain of sand there is a cause; In every blade of grass, a purpose. Even the Children of Man have a place within the Seasons."
The elkenbeast's ears flatten back against its head but it offers no response.
The elkenbeast seems pleased by your answer but doesn't offer any response to it. It continues to gaze deep into your eyes.
The elkenbeast blinks its glassy eyes and nods its head. "I wait for time." It backs away and begins to graze on non-existent grass. Its hooves click and clatter against the ancient stone.
The ghostly animal ignores your question, seemingly content to graze on dust and cobwebs.
Leave.
<StartAction>[Animal Empathy]</Start> Whisper to the ghostly elkenbeast.
"There be any way me can help?"
"Is there anything I can do to help?"
"What happen to you?"
"What happened to you?"
"What be this noble cause you die for?"
"What noble cause did you die for?"
"Me wish me knew my cause."
"I wish I knew my cause."
"Me no have a cause."
"I have no cause."
"Me have cause but it not be noble."
"My cause is far from noble."
"Yuh, me too. Noble cause."
"I died for a noble cause as well."
"Who you wait here for?"
"Who do you wait here for?"
"What you mean?"
"What do you mean?"
